Anthropogenic emissions of carbon dioxide from fossil fuels and land use change have warmed Earth by approximately 1°C since the late 19th century (
 
  1
 ), with virtual certainty of continued warming during the 21st century (
 
  2
 ). Warming leads to an accelerated hydrologic cycle due to the exponential relationship between temperature and saturation vapor pressure (
 
  3
 ) and to changes in moisture delivery systems such as El Niño (
 
  4
 ), jet streams (
 
  5
 ), and storm tracks (
 
  6
 ). While changes in mean precipitation are uncertain and vary by region (
 
  2
 ), changes in temperature will likely result in higher vapor pressure deficit (VPD) and higher precipitation variability (
 
  2
 , 
 
  3
 ). Globally, changes in the variability of precipitation are likely to be larger than changes in mean precipitation and nearly ubiquitous across all regions (
 
  3
 ).
